				\begin{document}$$ R_{o} = - \frac{{\log \left( {\frac{1 - AR}{So}} \right)}}{{AR - \left( {1 - So} \right)}} $$\end{document}Ro=-log1-ARSoAR-1-So. The formula uses the attack rate (AR) i.e. the fraction of population ultimately infected. In the traditional SIR (Susceptible, Infected and Recovered) model of disease spread, the attack rate is associated to the basic reproduction number. The initial percentage of susceptible population is taken as So. The data used in the analysis are those countries which have more than 10,000 (2019-nCoV) as available in https://www.worldometers.info/coronavirus/#countries. This will help to get a clear picture of the Ro, (1 − 1/Ro) and 1/Ro values in further modelling process of the data.
